    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{\frac{r}{r^{2}-9}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-9}}}{{\frac{1}{r+9}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{\left(r-1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+9\right)}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}, r\ne -9</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{\frac{r}{r^{2}-9}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-9}}}{{\frac{1}{r+9}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{\frac{r}{r^{2}-9}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-9}}</m> and <m>{\frac{1}{r+9}}</m>, which is <m>{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+9\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{\frac{r}{r^{2}-9}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-9}}}{{\frac{1}{r+9}}} \amp = \frac{{\frac{r}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}-\frac{1}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}}}{{\frac{1}{r+9}}} \\
    \amp = \frac{({\frac{r}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}-\frac{1}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}})\cdot{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+9\right)}}{({\frac{1}{r+9}})\cdot{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+9\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{\frac{r}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}\mathopen{}\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+9\right)-\frac{1}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}\mathopen{}\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+9\right)}}{{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}}, r \ne -9 \\
    \amp = \frac{{r\mathopen{}\left(r+9\right)-\left(r+9\right)}}{{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}}, r \ne -9\\
    \amp = \frac{{r^{2}+8r-9}}{{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}}, r \ne -9 \\
    \amp = {\frac{\left(r-1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+9\right)}{\left(r+3\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-3\right)}, r\ne -9}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since <m>r+9</m> was canceled, <m>r \ne -9</m> is a lost domain condition.</p>
<p>Although <m>r-3</m> and <m>r + 3</m> were also canceled, <m>r \ne 3</m> and <m>r \ne -3</m> are not lost domain conditions because they are implied in the solution.</p>
</solution>
